contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

01:39.165 --> 01:42.134
 Let me guess.

01:42.135 --> 01:44.002
 -lndiana Jones?
 -Yes.

01:44.003 --> 01:47.003
 Cast your mind back to "Indiana
 Jones and the Last Crusade."

01:47.440 --> 01:49.575
 Indy and his father
 are racing away from the Nazis

01:49.576 --> 01:50.409
 on a motorcycle.

01:50.410 --> 01:53.045
 Nazis come up alongside them
 and are about to get them,

01:53.046 --> 01:54.346
 but Indy doesn't have a weapon.

01:54.347 --> 01:56.281
 Quickly thinking,
 he grabs a flagpole,

01:56.282 --> 01:58.484
 jams it in the front spokes
 of the Nazi motorcycle and...

01:58.485 --> 02:01.485
 The motorcycle flips up
 in the air, end over end.

02:01.754 --> 02:02.888
 Bad time for the Nazi.

02:02.889 --> 02:04.022
 Exactly.

02:04.023 --> 02:06.525
 That is our movie myth.

02:06.526 --> 02:09.526
 NARRATOR: It's a classic scene
 from the silver screen.

02:09.529 --> 02:12.529
 The Doctors Jones,
 Junior and Senior,

02:12.599 --> 02:15.599
 are being chased
 by the Third Reich on bikes.

02:17.203 --> 02:20.203
 But a flagpole in the front
 wheel of the nearest Nazi,

02:21.040 --> 02:24.040
 and a motorcycle flip-out
 sees our hero escape

02:24.310 --> 02:26.078
 with a trademark cheesy grin.

02:26.079 --> 02:29.047
 This one's really interesting
 from a physics sense.

02:29.048 --> 02:31.450
 Because when I look
 at that scene,

02:31.451 --> 02:33.952
 it doesn't seem awkward
 or out of place.

02:33.953 --> 02:35.654
 But it does beg the question,

02:35.655 --> 02:38.257
 is it really that easy
 to redirect all the energy

02:38.258 --> 02:41.258
 that's going this way
 to going that way?

02:41.427 --> 02:42.728
 I'm thinking
 that we break it down

02:42.729 --> 02:44.897
 to its constituent components,
 test each one,

02:44.898 --> 02:46.532
 and then put them
 all back together

02:46.533 --> 02:47.933
 for a full-sized finale.

02:47.934 --> 02:48.934
 This will be fun.

02:48.935 --> 02:51.503
 It's been years
 since I've been on a motorcycle.

02:51.504 --> 02:53.605
 Ever since that -- that gang,
 right?

02:53.606 --> 02:55.007
 [ Horn honking ]

02:55.008 --> 02:56.642
 NARRATOR:
 So, first things first.

02:56.643 --> 02:59.643
 It's a motorcycle myth,
 and we'll be needing a...

03:00.213 --> 03:01.313
 JAMIE:
 That's a bike.

03:01.314 --> 03:02.414
 NARRATOR: Exactly.

03:02.415 --> 03:04.416
 ADAM:
 Aw, it's lovely.

03:04.417 --> 03:06.818
 Actually, we rode across the
 country in one of these things.

03:06.819 --> 03:07.686
 No way.

03:07.687 --> 03:09.655
 I'm just reeling from learning
 something about you

03:09.656 --> 03:10.656
 I didn't know.

03:10.657 --> 03:12.691
 It seems that there's
 a never-ending supply of those.

03:12.692 --> 03:14.860
 NARRATOR:
 Okay, it may be old-fashioned,

03:14.861 --> 03:17.496
 but the movie bikes
 are vintage World War I I.

03:17.497 --> 03:18.630
 ADAM:
 I know what you're saying.

03:18.631 --> 03:20.332
 You're saying
 this really doesn't look like

03:20.333 --> 03:23.333
 a vintage World War I I era
 motorcycle, and it isn't.

03:23.770 --> 03:26.770
 In fact, it's from 1981, but
 it is the exact model of bike

03:28.408 --> 03:30.876
 used by the stunt men
 to perform their stunts

03:30.877 --> 03:32.778
 for "Indiana Jones
 and the Last Crusade,"

03:32.779 --> 03:35.779
 which means that it,
 and not some vintage bike,

03:36.015 --> 03:39.015
 is the perfect test platform
 for us for this for this myth.

03:40.086 --> 03:41.520
 NARRATOR:
 Now that that's sorted,

03:41.521 --> 03:43.922
 let's kick things off
 as Adam and Jamie focus

03:43.923 --> 03:45.757
 on the first aspect of the myth.

03:45.758 --> 03:47.893
 ADAM: Since this myth is all
 about the poking of a flagpole

03:47.894 --> 03:49.328
 into the spokes of a motorcycle,

03:49.329 --> 03:50.829
 one of the things
 we want to know is,

03:50.830 --> 03:53.830
 how fast can we poke a flagpole?

03:54.834 --> 03:56.602
 NARRATOR:
 Because once they know the speed

03:56.603 --> 03:59.603
 of a human flagpole poke...

04:01.975 --> 04:03.175
 ADAM:
 Nice, tiger.

04:03.176 --> 04:06.011
 NARRATOR:... they can calibrate
 their remaining tests

04:06.012 --> 04:07.012
 to just that.

04:07.013 --> 04:09.281
 Just plain funny to watch you
 exert yourself like that.

04:09.282 --> 04:12.282
 I don't know why, exactly.
 It just is.

04:12.619 --> 04:13.819
 High comedy.

04:13.820 --> 04:15.587
 -Whatever floats your goat.
 -[ Laughs ]

04:15.588 --> 04:18.588
 NARRATOR: And the high comedy
 on the high speed

04:18.825 --> 04:21.825
 reveals the magic number to be
 30 miles per hour.

04:22.395 --> 04:24.896
 Cue part two
 of the experiment --

04:24.897 --> 04:27.699
 a remote-control
 flagpole thruster.

04:27.700 --> 04:29.868
 You might remember
 this puppy right here

04:29.869 --> 04:32.869
 from "Birds on a Truck" because
 this was our pigeon catcher.

04:33.539 --> 04:36.341
 NARRATOR: Yep, it's not a prop
 from "Mad Max."

04:36.342 --> 04:38.744
 It really is a pigeon catcher.

04:38.745 --> 04:40.345
 ADAM: [ Laughs ]

04:40.346 --> 04:42.180
 NARRATOR:
 Not that it caught any pigeons.

04:42.181 --> 04:44.616
 JAMIE: It has an air reservoir.
 It has a valve.

04:44.617 --> 04:46.985
 It has everything we need
 to shoot the stick

04:46.986 --> 04:48.754
 into the wheels
 of the motorcycle.

04:48.755 --> 04:51.755
 In 3, 2, 1...

04:55.128 --> 04:57.829
 [ Laughs ]

04:57.830 --> 05:00.098
 NARRATOR:
 Yeah, that looked a tad faster

05:00.099 --> 05:02.200
 than 30 miles an hour to me.

05:02.201 --> 05:03.769
 But let's see what Adam thinks.

05:03.770 --> 05:05.170
 ADAM: One.

05:05.171 --> 05:06.605
 [ Wood rattling ]

05:06.606 --> 05:09.606
 [ Laughs ]

05:09.742 --> 05:11.310
 That might be a little too fast.

05:11.311 --> 05:13.045
 NARRATOR: Hmm.
 That's what I said.

05:13.046 --> 05:16.046
 Is everybody okay?

05:16.683 --> 05:18.083
 JAMIE:
 That's dangerous.

05:18.084 --> 05:21.084
 Yeah, we might have to
 tune that one back.

05:21.821 --> 05:24.089
 I'm not gonna get tired of that.

05:24.090 --> 05:26.124
 NARRATOR: And so, to get
 the speed they need --

05:26.125 --> 05:28.427
 around 30 miles per hour...

05:28.428 --> 05:31.428
 ADAM: This is
 an exceedingly weird operation.

05:32.432 --> 05:35.133
 NARRATOR:... they add some hose
 to decrease the pressure.

05:35.134 --> 05:38.134
 Firing in 3, 2, 1.

05:39.806 --> 05:40.772
 That might be it.

05:40.773 --> 05:42.507
 ADAM: That's it.
 That's the butter zone.

05:42.508 --> 05:45.508
 12 p.s. i., we get
 28 1/2 miles per hour.

05:46.412 --> 05:47.946
 That's perfect.

05:47.947 --> 05:49.681
 NARRATOR:
 As odd as this sounds,

05:49.682 --> 05:51.583
 after destroying
 their wooden backstop,

05:51.584 --> 05:54.584
 they finally got the ex-pigeon
 catcher throwing a flagpole

05:55.955 --> 05:58.955
 at a realistic speed.

06:05.365 --> 06:06.998
 TORY:
 I'm free!

06:06.999 --> 06:08.900
 This might sound crazy,
 but a lot of the fans are saying

06:08.901 --> 06:11.336
 that you can actually make rope
 out of toilet paper,

06:11.337 --> 06:12.404
 and it'll be strong enough

06:12.405 --> 06:14.840
 that you could scale down
 a jail wall and escape.

06:14.841 --> 06:16.274
 Toilet paper?
 Are you serious?

06:16.275 --> 06:17.509
 GRANT:
 Well, if we're gonna do that,

06:17.510 --> 06:19.644
 I think we should do
 the all-time classic --

06:19.645 --> 06:21.146
 making a rope out of bedsheets.

06:21.147 --> 06:22.447
 I know it's kind of out there,

06:22.448 --> 06:24.082
 but let's also do
 the "Rapunzel" version of this,

06:24.083 --> 06:25.817
 where you make a rope
 out of hair.

06:25.818 --> 06:28.553
 -Ew.
 -lck

06:28.554 --> 06:31.554
 NARRATOR: Any prison break worth
 its place in urban folklore

06:32.125 --> 06:35.125
 involves a death-defying descent
 from a great height...

06:37.363 --> 06:40.265
...including
 these fan-site fables.

06:40.266 --> 06:43.266
 Desperate convicts eager to be
 ex-convicts have escaped jail

06:44.537 --> 06:46.972
 with the apparent aid
 of cell-made ropes

06:46.973 --> 06:49.741
 of toilet paper and bedsheets.

06:49.742 --> 06:52.742
 And if you include
 Rapunzel's luscious locks,

06:53.146 --> 06:56.146
 that's three harebrained
 escape plans to test.

06:57.216 --> 06:58.650
 So, how are we gonna test this?

06:58.651 --> 07:01.386
 Why don't we each take one of
 the materials, make our ropes,

07:01.387 --> 07:04.189
 and see which one of us makes it
 down the side of the building?

07:04.190 --> 07:05.690
 And may the best rope win.

07:05.691 --> 07:07.993
 Wait, wait.
 I want bedsheets, then.

07:07.994 --> 07:09.227
 Too late.

07:09.228 --> 07:11.930
 NARRATOR: Yes, in
 a vertigo-inducing finale...

07:11.931 --> 07:13.432
 KARI: Aah!

07:13.433 --> 07:15.033
 Oh, my God.
 I want to throw up.

07:15.034 --> 07:18.034
 NARRATOR:... our fun-loving
 criminals will find out for real

07:18.237 --> 07:21.237
 if the ropes made
 from their mythical materials

07:21.574 --> 07:24.543
 will aid and abet
 their jailbreak.

07:24.544 --> 07:26.678
 Stupidest idea ever.

07:26.679 --> 07:29.214
 NARRATOR: Or send them
 plummeting to their doom.

07:29.215 --> 07:30.015
 Ow!

07:30.016 --> 07:31.883
 NARRATOR:
 But before all that,

07:31.884 --> 07:34.119
 let's take you
 back to the beginning...

07:34.120 --> 07:37.120
...where Kari's plan
 for a braided escape

07:37.256 --> 07:39.458
 is giving her a bad hair day.

07:39.459 --> 07:40.892
 KARI: Is this not
 the most disgusting thing

07:40.893 --> 07:43.893
 you've ever seen --
 an entire box of just hair?

07:45.164 --> 07:46.832
 NARRATOR:
 Yes, coming in at number one

07:46.833 --> 07:49.434
 on the weirdest
 raw-material chart

07:49.435 --> 07:52.304
 are 50 human-hair ponytails.

07:52.305 --> 07:55.305
 KARI: We have to break out of a
 building that's 14 stories high,

07:55.641 --> 07:58.641
 so I have to make a rope
 that is 140 feet long.

08:01.180 --> 08:03.248
 I think the difficulty here
 is not gonna necessarily

08:03.249 --> 08:05.817
 be the strength of the hair,
 'cause this feels really strong.

08:05.818 --> 08:08.520
 I think it's gonna be where
 the hair splices together.

08:08.521 --> 08:10.922
 I have to come up with some sort
 of knotting or braiding system

08:10.923 --> 08:13.625
 that it won't slide apart
 and, you know, 100 feet down,

08:13.626 --> 08:15.894
 I'm not just gonna plummet
 to the earth.

08:15.895 --> 08:17.596
 And it's gross.

08:17.597 --> 08:19.598
 NARRATOR: Meanwhile,
 Grant's mythical method

08:19.599 --> 08:22.599
 is a little more conventional
 and a film-fugitive favorite.

08:23.469 --> 08:26.371
 GRANT: In order to make sure we
 have maximum authenticity here,

08:26.372 --> 08:28.673
 we've gotten these bedsheets

08:28.674 --> 08:31.076
 from our friends
 in Alameda County,

08:31.077 --> 08:33.945
 and they're actual
 county-jail linens.

08:33.946 --> 08:35.847
 NARRATOR:
 And finally Tory,

08:35.847 --> 08:38.783
 who has some serious
 tensile strength issues

08:38.784 --> 08:41.784
 with his authentic
 one-ply prison-issue tissue.

08:42.655 --> 08:45.023
 [ Metal rattling ]

08:45.024 --> 08:46.992
 There you have it.
 It's not strong enough.

08:46.993 --> 08:49.160
 NARRATOR:
 But he's a man with a plan.

08:49.161 --> 08:50.595
 TORY:
 If you look at the toilet paper,

08:50.596 --> 08:52.998
 it's perforated
 for your convenience

08:52.999 --> 08:55.200
 of pulling off
 one sheet at a time.

08:55.201 --> 08:57.969
 Already it's got
 this built-in weak link.

08:57.970 --> 08:59.905
 So I think twisting it,
 rolling it

08:59.906 --> 09:02.906
 will give me the extra strength
 that I need.

09:03.142 --> 09:04.142
 Look at that.

09:04.143 --> 09:06.878
 The same amount of toilet paper
 just wrapped up

09:06.879 --> 09:08.947
 is strong enough
 to now hold the three kilos.

09:08.948 --> 09:11.948
 So this is the way I'm gonna
 make my toilet-paper rope.

09:12.585 --> 09:13.585
 -MAN: Fire!
 -Go!

09:13.586 --> 09:15.320
 NARRATOR:
 Adam and Jamie's past crusade

09:15.321 --> 09:17.923
 to hold Hollywood
 to scientific account...

09:17.924 --> 09:19.891
 -Whoo!
 -ADAM: Oh, that's great!

09:19.892 --> 09:22.093
 NARRATOR:... has given the team
 some memorable moments

09:22.094 --> 09:23.728
 of movie mayhem.

09:23.729 --> 09:26.398
 MAN:
 Buster's on the ground.

09:26.399 --> 09:28.333
 NARRATOR:
 But on this last crusade,

09:28.334 --> 09:30.602
 the team are tackling
 the tall tale

09:30.603 --> 09:33.603
 that a stick between the spokes
 can cause...

09:33.906 --> 09:36.906
...a head-over-handlebars flip.

09:38.477 --> 09:41.079
 So far they've got their bike

09:41.080 --> 09:44.080
 and rigged a remote-control
 flagpole thruster.

09:46.285 --> 09:47.619
 So, what's next?

09:47.620 --> 09:49.854
 JAMIE: When this bike is moving
 at highway speeds,

09:49.855 --> 09:52.855
 the spokes are going so fast,
 you can hardly see them.

09:53.359 --> 09:55.327
 So what we need to find out
 is whether it's possible

09:55.328 --> 09:58.328
 for a human to thrust a stick
 into those spokes

09:59.165 --> 10:01.733
 fast enough to get them
 cleanly through there,

10:01.734 --> 10:04.734
 and then, once that occurs,
 what happens to the wheel.

10:05.438 --> 10:08.239
 NARRATOR: And to get the wheel
 spinning at chasing speeds --

10:08.240 --> 10:11.240
 50 miles per hour --
 Adam whips up a dynamometer.

10:11.844 --> 10:14.844
 And now it's time for the old
 spoke-and-poke test.

10:15.815 --> 10:17.749
 NARRATOR:
 So with the bike secured,

10:17.750 --> 10:20.685
 this test is all about the space
 between the spokes

10:20.686 --> 10:22.887
 and not the full flip.

10:22.888 --> 10:24.222
 This is gonna be cool.

10:24.223 --> 10:26.891
 NARRATOR: Will a flagpole thrust
 at realistic speed

10:26.892 --> 10:28.627
 actually penetrate the wheel?

10:28.628 --> 10:31.628
 3, 2, 1.

10:32.365 --> 10:33.465
 NARRATOR:
 Apparently not.

10:33.466 --> 10:35.367
 Well, that was
 a bit of a letdown.

10:35.368 --> 10:38.368
 NARRATOR: Yes, the stick
 just bounced right back out.

10:39.472 --> 10:42.472
 And after a second test
 under the same conditions...

10:43.542 --> 10:45.710
...produces a similar result,

10:45.711 --> 10:48.013
 the guys decide
 they are missing the point.

10:48.014 --> 10:51.014
 Firing, 3, 2, 1.

10:52.018 --> 10:53.852
 NARRATOR: Perfect.
 Penetration.

10:53.853 --> 10:55.186
 Wheel stoppage.

10:55.187 --> 10:58.187
 And, as a bonus,
 some controlled mayhem.

10:59.225 --> 11:01.259
 We broke some stuff.

11:01.260 --> 11:02.727
 JAMIE:
 We successfully stopped

11:02.728 --> 11:04.462
 the wheel with the stick,
 and that's great.

11:04.463 --> 11:07.463
 That's 15 pounds coming to a
 dead stop from 50 miles an hour.

11:08.701 --> 11:10.802
 But this was a stationary test.

11:10.803 --> 11:12.637
 When we go out on the road
 with this,

11:12.638 --> 11:15.140
 there are hundreds of pounds
 in this bike,

11:15.141 --> 11:18.109
 plus the rider,
 that want to keep on going.

11:18.110 --> 11:20.612
 And that's where
 the real fun is gonna start.

11:20.613 --> 11:22.280
 NARRATOR:
 So it's full scale ahead,

11:22.281 --> 11:25.281
 and the plan in the can
 looks a lot like this.

11:25.518 --> 11:27.318
 At the push of a button,

11:27.319 --> 11:30.319
 the bike and Buster
 will begin freewheeling.

11:30.690 --> 11:33.690
 That, in turn, will trigger
 the flagpole flinger

11:34.193 --> 11:37.193
 and jam the stick
 into the spokes.

11:37.496 --> 11:40.031
 And to get things rolling
 in the right direction,

11:40.032 --> 11:42.400
 Adam's reinventing the wheel.

11:42.401 --> 11:44.436
 ADAM: Well, the first problem
 I think we've got to solve

11:44.437 --> 11:47.138
 is exemplified by taking a look
 at this footage again.

11:47.139 --> 11:49.307
 Yeah. See that?
 Okay.

11:49.308 --> 11:52.308
 The hubbed spoked wheel
 is not really ideal for us

11:52.712 --> 11:53.812
 to shove a stick into

11:53.813 --> 11:56.813
 'cause those spokes
 are not gonna stay put.

11:56.916 --> 11:59.851
 We need a wheel that can stay
 put under continued abuse

11:59.852 --> 12:02.852
 for repeated tests, and we're
 gonna use steel plate to do it.

12:03.923 --> 12:05.757
 We've had two of these
 plasma-cut

12:05.758 --> 12:07.025
 out of quarter-inch steel plate.

12:07.026 --> 12:09.360
 We're gonna bolt them
 to one of the motorcycle rims,

12:09.361 --> 12:10.829
 have a tire put back on it

12:10.830 --> 12:13.798
 and a couple of flange-mounted
 pillow blocks on the axle,

12:13.799 --> 12:16.668
 and that ought to hold up to
 everything we can throw at it.

12:16.669 --> 12:18.269
 [ Laughs ]

12:18.270 --> 12:20.472
 The Road Warrior would be proud.

12:20.473 --> 12:23.473
 This thing is absolutely
 as solid as a rock.

12:23.809 --> 12:26.809
 It's perfect.

12:28.180 --> 12:29.214
 [ Tires screeching ]

12:29.215 --> 12:31.483
 NARRATOR:
 For the prison-break parable...

12:31.484 --> 12:33.618
 This place can't hold me!

12:33.619 --> 12:36.087
 NARRATOR:
...Grant "Iron Man" Imahara...

12:36.088 --> 12:37.789
 I'm bustin' out of here, see?

12:37.790 --> 12:40.091
 NARRATOR:
...Kari "Knuckles" Byron...

12:40.092 --> 12:42.026
 -MAN: Come on.
 -I was framed!

12:42.027 --> 12:44.662
 NARRATOR:... and
 "Don" Salvatore Belleci...

12:44.663 --> 12:45.730
 Framed, I tell you!

12:45.731 --> 12:47.665
 NARRATOR:
...are pretending to be put away

12:47.666 --> 12:49.467
 in order to break out.

12:49.468 --> 12:52.468
 Prisoners, step in.
 Lockdown.

12:54.540 --> 12:57.342
 NARRATOR: They're going to find
 out if you can effect an escape

12:57.343 --> 13:00.343
 with ropes made of bedsheets,
 toilet paper, and hair.

13:01.547 --> 13:04.249
 KARI: My collection of hair
 gathered from the shower

13:04.250 --> 13:06.818
 and all the rattails
 I've been stealing...

13:06.819 --> 13:08.153
 Aah!

13:08.154 --> 13:11.154
...I will have no problem making
 a rope and getting out of here.

13:11.423 --> 13:13.358
 NARRATOR:
 But despite being forced to use

13:13.359 --> 13:15.760
 authentic cell-made materials...

13:15.761 --> 13:18.761
 Warden, I got diarrhea.
 I need more toilet paper.

13:19.198 --> 13:20.899
 NARRATOR:... the guys
 won't really have to prepare

13:20.900 --> 13:23.900
 their escape in their cells.

13:24.236 --> 13:26.237
 They get to do that
 back at the shop,

13:26.238 --> 13:27.705
 where Tory has worked out

13:27.706 --> 13:30.706
 that if he twists
 one-ply prison-issue tissue,

13:30.776 --> 13:32.277
 it becomes less fragile.

13:32.278 --> 13:34.546
 TORY: As you can see,
 I'm twisting the toilet paper

13:34.547 --> 13:35.613
 into little strings.

13:35.614 --> 13:37.649
 Once I have enough strings,
 I'll weave it into a rope,

13:37.650 --> 13:40.650
 and hopefully that will be
 strong enough to hold my weight,

13:40.820 --> 13:42.754
 and that will be my ticket
 out of this joint.

13:42.755 --> 13:45.557
 And this process is taking
 a long time,

13:45.558 --> 13:47.458
 but, let's face it, I'm in jail.

13:47.459 --> 13:49.227
 I got nothing but time.

13:49.228 --> 13:52.228
 Someday I'll be free 

13:52.631 --> 13:53.965
 Bing 

13:53.966 --> 13:55.533
 NARRATOR:
 It may be time-consuming,

13:55.534 --> 13:58.236
 but before
 modern manufacturing techniques,

13:58.237 --> 14:01.237
 this is exactly
 how real rope was made.

14:01.340 --> 14:04.340
 Fibers of material
 were twisted into yarns.

14:04.376 --> 14:05.743
 A few of these yarns

14:05.744 --> 14:08.744
 were twisted in the opposite
 direction to form threads,

14:09.048 --> 14:11.182
 and, again, several of these

14:11.183 --> 14:14.052
 were counter-twisted
 to form rope.

14:14.053 --> 14:17.053
 So it might sound crazy, but
 Tory could be on to something.

14:18.190 --> 14:21.190
 [ Laughs ] I'm gonna get
 out of jail in no time.

14:21.393 --> 14:23.461
 NARRATOR: Meanwhile,
 Kari's about to find out

14:23.462 --> 14:26.462
 if her plan for a braided escape
 is even viable.

14:27.032 --> 14:29.968
 KARI: I'm a little nervous
 about the strength of the hair,

14:29.969 --> 14:31.536
 so I've got a knotted piece here

14:31.537 --> 14:34.272
 that I was actually just gonna
 try my weight on.

14:34.273 --> 14:37.273
 I'm really kind of nervous
 about this because of...

14:38.544 --> 14:39.844
 [Bleep]

14:39.845 --> 14:42.845
...that factor.

14:42.948 --> 14:45.817
 Maybe I need to find some
 inmates with some less healthy,

14:45.818 --> 14:46.985
 slippery hair --

14:46.986 --> 14:49.986
 some good, fried-out,
 bleached-blond inmates.

14:50.289 --> 14:53.289
 NARRATOR: Yeah, or maybe,
 just like a conventional rope,

14:53.726 --> 14:56.527
 you could braid a number of
 those single strands together.

14:56.528 --> 14:58.062
 KARI:
 I'm gonna take three braids

14:58.063 --> 15:00.198
 and tie them all into one braid

15:00.199 --> 15:01.933
 so that it's sort of
 how rope works,

15:01.934 --> 15:04.934
 where one fails, it has two more
 to kind of depend on.

15:05.871 --> 15:08.339
 And hopefully that can give it
 more strength.

15:08.340 --> 15:10.708
 Unfortunately,
 I'm getting claw hand

15:10.709 --> 15:12.710
 from, like, all the braiding.

15:12.711 --> 15:14.178
 Ugh.

15:14.179 --> 15:16.114
 NARRATOR:
 And that just leaves Grant,

15:16.115 --> 15:19.115
 who got lucky, with the least
 labor-intensive material.

15:19.485 --> 15:20.985
 GRANT:
 The bedsheet is beautiful

15:20.986 --> 15:23.655
 because you can go
 to the prison laundry,

15:23.656 --> 15:25.490
 steal as many as you need.

15:25.491 --> 15:28.491
 You don't need a hundred years
 to make your bedsheet rope.

15:28.861 --> 15:31.861
 You need about, I don't know,
 maybe two hours,

15:32.064 --> 15:34.732
 and you're climbing
 your way to freedom.

15:34.733 --> 15:36.701
 NARRATOR:
 However, the toilet-paper plan

15:36.702 --> 15:39.637
 is taking a lot, lot longer.

15:39.638 --> 15:41.439
 I need to spread my wings
 and fly.

15:41.440 --> 15:42.974
 NARRATOR:
 So, to speed things up,

15:42.975 --> 15:45.975
 our crafty criminal uses
 his mastermind to good effect

15:48.447 --> 15:51.447
 by twisting multiple strands
 at once and cheating.

15:53.252 --> 15:55.186
 TORY: So, I've taken five sheets
 of toilet paper,

15:55.187 --> 15:56.988
 twisted them together
 to create this.

15:56.989 --> 15:59.057
 Now I'm gonna take three
 of these, wrap them together,

15:59.058 --> 16:01.025
 and then take that
 and wrap that together

16:01.026 --> 16:03.761
 and hopefully create a rope
 that's gonna be strong enough

16:03.762 --> 16:04.963
 to hold up my weight.

16:04.964 --> 16:06.731
 NARRATOR:
 Meanwhile, over in Grant's cell,

16:06.732 --> 16:09.732
 he's testing to see if
 the sheets can take the strain.

16:10.169 --> 16:12.937
 GRANT: So, what we have here
 is a single standard

16:12.938 --> 16:15.938
 Alameda County bedsheet
 with a knot tied at the top,

16:16.275 --> 16:18.910
 threaded through
 150 pounds of weight,

16:18.911 --> 16:21.279
 which is equivalent
 to my body weight.

16:21.280 --> 16:22.647
 And as you can see,

16:22.648 --> 16:25.049
 it's actually doing quite well
 so far.

16:25.050 --> 16:27.085
 NARRATOR:
 Outside in the exercise yard,

16:27.086 --> 16:30.086
 Tory is also ready
 for a strength test.

16:31.390 --> 16:32.557
 This might work!

16:32.558 --> 16:34.292
 NARRATOR:
 Kari, however, is still

16:34.293 --> 16:36.527
 desperately braiding
 and plaiting.

16:36.528 --> 16:39.528
 She's more concerned about
 the hair's joints and splices

16:39.765 --> 16:42.765
 than its tensile strength.

16:43.168 --> 16:46.168
 After all, keratin, the major
 protein component of hair,

16:46.772 --> 16:49.407
 is as hard as nails --
 literally.

16:49.408 --> 16:52.408
 It's also the stuff that forms
 horns, claws, and hooves.

16:54.013 --> 16:57.013
 The question is,
 will it also make rope?

16:59.551 --> 17:01.486
 Jamie and Adam
 are flipping out...

17:01.487 --> 17:03.388
 That might be a little too fast.

17:03.389 --> 17:03.855
 Firing.

17:03.856 --> 17:05.323
 NARRATOR:
...testing the movie myth

17:05.324 --> 17:08.324
 that jamming a stick
 between the spokes...

17:08.894 --> 17:11.894
...will cause
 a motorcycle flip-out.

17:12.231 --> 17:14.632
 But they've got
 a tough build ahead.

17:14.633 --> 17:16.134
 In order to go full scale
 with this,

17:16.135 --> 17:19.135
 we need to both be able to hold
 this bike and let go of it

17:20.406 --> 17:22.140
 at very precise timing.

17:22.141 --> 17:24.175
 So we're gonna start
 by building a trailer

17:24.175 --> 17:26.944
 that holds it upright,
 that, on the push of a button,

17:26.944 --> 17:29.313
 releases it,
 and then, once it's released,

17:29.314 --> 17:32.314
 will fire a stick right through
 those front spokes.

17:34.119 --> 17:37.119
 NARRATOR: In engineering terms,
 there's a mountain to climb.

17:37.189 --> 17:40.189
 And what better way to show the
 passage of time than a montage?

17:47.866 --> 17:50.866
 And a cross-dissolve later,
 the rig is ready to roll.

17:51.437 --> 17:54.437
 But before the cameras do, the
 team needs a change of scenery.

17:55.374 --> 17:57.875
 -Ready?
 -Yep. Let's go.

17:57.876 --> 17:59.077
 [ Tires screeching ]

17:59.078 --> 18:01.979
 NARRATOR: And the location
 they've chosen is, surprise,

18:01.980 --> 18:03.681
 the disused runway at Alameda.

18:03.682 --> 18:05.550
 ADAM: It's a good day
 for a motorcycle accident.

18:05.551 --> 18:08.551
 -JAMIE: I think so.
 -Let's make a few.

18:09.021 --> 18:12.021
 NARRATOR: Unlikely to have
 a motorcycle accident is Jamie,

18:12.991 --> 18:15.991
 our very own cross-country
 motorbiking Mythbuster.

18:16.795 --> 18:18.696
 -But Adam?
 -ADAM: Let's trade.

18:18.697 --> 18:21.165
 NARRATOR:
 Well, that's a different story.

18:21.166 --> 18:23.968
 [ Engine revs ]

18:23.969 --> 18:26.838
 How do you undo this?

18:26.839 --> 18:29.839
 I'm not so sure
 this is a good idea.

18:30.175 --> 18:33.175
 Adam on a motorcycle?

18:34.580 --> 18:37.580
 Even with seat belts,
 I worry about Adam.

18:41.220 --> 18:42.954
 Are you done yet?
 We got some work to do.

18:42.955 --> 18:44.789
 -Let's get busy.
 -All right. Let's do it.

18:44.790 --> 18:47.758
 -[ Engine stalls ]
 -Oh! Aw.

18:47.759 --> 18:50.495
 NARRATOR: So while Jamie
 reassembles the trailer

18:50.496 --> 18:51.729
 and release rig,

18:51.730 --> 18:54.730
 Adam brightens up the bike
 for its big scene.

18:55.267 --> 18:58.267
 And with Buster's ride
 secured to the trailer...

18:59.104 --> 19:00.605
...he's ready for a test run.

19:00.606 --> 19:02.340
 ADAM: This may look pretty
 straightforward,

19:02.341 --> 19:03.774
 but, actually,
 it's a pretty complicated rig,

19:03.775 --> 19:06.244
 and there's a lot of little
 things which we're not sure

19:06.245 --> 19:09.180
 exactly how they might react
 to getting up to speed.

19:09.181 --> 19:10.481
 So that's the first thing
 we're gonna do --

19:10.482 --> 19:13.482
 get the whole rig up to speed
 and just see how it runs.

19:13.919 --> 19:15.486
 NARRATOR:
 And with the truck easing up

19:15.487 --> 19:17.588
 to 25 miles per hour...

19:17.589 --> 19:19.023
 JAMIE: I don't see
 any problem with that.

19:19.024 --> 19:20.525
 NARRATOR:
...Buster stays upright

19:20.526 --> 19:22.960
 and has no problems
 keeping in line.

19:22.961 --> 19:24.729
 Now it's time
 to start the mayhem.

19:24.730 --> 19:27.730
 Start the mayhem!

19:28.367 --> 19:30.334
 Yeah! [ Growls ]

19:30.335 --> 19:32.036
 NARRATOR:
 Jailed for science,

19:32.037 --> 19:35.037
 Kari, Grant, and Tory are going
 a little stir crazy.

19:36.842 --> 19:38.676
 Man, I got to get out of here.

19:38.677 --> 19:40.645
 If only we could figure out
 a way to escape.

19:40.646 --> 19:42.480
 If only we had a rope
 or something.

19:42.481 --> 19:43.948
 NARRATOR:
 Yes, they're putting

19:43.949 --> 19:46.949
 three mythical rope-making
 materials to the test.

19:48.053 --> 19:51.053
 The hair's been braided,
 the toilet paper twisted,

19:51.390 --> 19:54.292
 and the sheets rolled
 and knotted,

19:54.293 --> 19:56.427
 which means
 our ingenious inmates

19:56.428 --> 19:58.896
 are ready to become outmates.

19:58.897 --> 20:01.199
 And the coop
 they'll be flying from

20:01.200 --> 20:04.200
 is the Alameda County
 Courthouse Jail.

20:05.103 --> 20:06.938
 They have to rappel
 from the roof

20:06.939 --> 20:09.473
 using only
 their cell-made ropes.

20:09.474 --> 20:11.075
 [ Creaking ]

20:11.076 --> 20:12.410
 [ Laughing ]
 Not bad.

20:12.411 --> 20:13.544
 All right, you guys.

20:13.545 --> 20:16.247
 This is the moment of truth
 for our prison-escape ropes.

20:16.248 --> 20:19.183
 We've got 100 % human hair,
 toilet-paper rope,

20:19.184 --> 20:21.686
 and the old-school classic,
 bedsheet.

20:21.687 --> 20:23.754
 Well, since yours is probably
 the most likely to work,

20:23.755 --> 20:25.690
 maybe you should go first
 to show us how it's done.

20:25.691 --> 20:26.958
 And then this way,
 we can test out

20:26.959 --> 20:29.427
 the SWAT team safety mechanism.

20:29.428 --> 20:31.729
 -[ Laughs ]
 -Fine. I will.

20:31.730 --> 20:33.431
 -Good luck, man.
 -All right.

20:33.432 --> 20:35.399
 -Freedom!
 -KARI: Good idea.

20:35.400 --> 20:38.400
 Him going first.
 I like that.

20:38.537 --> 20:41.405
 NARRATOR: So Grant,
 the nominated human guinea pig,

20:41.406 --> 20:42.406
 is first up.

20:42.407 --> 20:45.407
 But rest assured,
 he's in safe hands.

20:45.844 --> 20:48.844
 Jack Tucker and Mike Norton
 are SWAT team rappel masters,

20:49.948 --> 20:52.550
 and they've rigged a harness
 and rope system

20:52.551 --> 20:55.551
 that will allow Grant
 to climb unassisted...

20:55.687 --> 20:56.787
 unless he falls.

20:56.788 --> 20:59.557
 Well, that certainly
 gets the juices flowing.

20:59.558 --> 21:01.659
 Um... yeah.

21:01.660 --> 21:04.660
 It's a little bit different
 perspective up here.

21:05.631 --> 21:08.631
 [ Dramatic music plays ]

21:09.434 --> 21:11.702
 Okay.
 I can do this.

21:11.703 --> 21:14.703
 NARRATOR: With every inch
 of that terrifying drop

21:14.873 --> 21:17.375
 playing on his mind,
 Grant forces himself

21:17.376 --> 21:19.610
 to focus on prepping
 for the climb.

21:19.611 --> 21:22.611
 GRANT: So this is the moment
 of truth for my bedsheet rope.

21:23.048 --> 21:26.048
 Can you actually escape using a
 bedsheet and not have it break?

21:28.053 --> 21:30.988
 [ Laughing nervously ]

21:30.989 --> 21:33.989
 Okay. It's long enough.

21:35.894 --> 21:37.228
 Okay.

21:37.229 --> 21:39.096
 [ Wind whistling ]

21:39.097 --> 21:42.033
 So careful observers may note
 that I'm wearing,

21:42.034 --> 21:45.034
 in addition to my standard
 prison garb, a safety harness.

21:45.237 --> 21:47.805
 Now, the important thing
 is that the safety harness

21:47.806 --> 21:50.806
 is only in case the rope breaks
 or there's some other problem.

21:52.978 --> 21:55.012
 Okay, you guys.
 I'm ready to go.

21:55.013 --> 21:58.013
 The bedsheet will be holding
 my entire weight the whole time.

21:59.551 --> 22:01.018
 Here I go.

22:01.019 --> 22:03.154
 NARRATOR:
 Grant's first careful steps

22:03.155 --> 22:06.155
 are onto a convenient ledge
 just over the edge.

22:07.459 --> 22:09.527
 Holy sheets!
 That's high!

22:09.528 --> 22:12.263
 NARRATOR: But from here on in,
 it's down to Grant

22:12.264 --> 22:13.998
 and those knotted bedsheets.

22:13.999 --> 22:15.333
 All right.
 You guys ready?

22:15.334 --> 22:16.334
 -KARI: Ready!
 -TORY: Yeah!

22:16.335 --> 22:19.335
 Here we go with the, uh,
 old-school bedsheet.

22:19.938 --> 22:22.506
 Be careful, little buddy!

22:22.507 --> 22:25.507
 NARRATOR: Despite the concern
 below, the early signs are good.

22:26.144 --> 22:27.745
 KARI: He's doing
 the walk-down-the-wall thing.

22:27.746 --> 22:28.813
 TORY: Oh.

22:28.814 --> 22:31.082
 It looks like he's done this
 before.

22:31.083 --> 22:33.250
 You've broken
 out of jail before?

22:33.251 --> 22:35.619
 KARI: Wow.
 Those are holding up.

22:35.620 --> 22:37.188
 NARRATOR:
 The bedsheets are holding up.

22:37.189 --> 22:39.223
 [ Chuckling ]
 He's getting tired.

22:39.224 --> 22:40.591
 KARI:
 Oh, man.

22:40.592 --> 22:43.592
 NARRATOR: The question now is,
 can Grant hold himself up?

22:43.695 --> 22:46.695
 -Ugh. Oh [bleep]
 -KARI: Oh, God.

22:47.265 --> 22:49.600
 He's just hanging!
 He's just hanging!

22:49.601 --> 22:52.601
 TORY: Hang on, buddy!
 Don't let go!

22:52.738 --> 22:54.438
 You're almost free!

22:54.439 --> 22:55.606
 Attaboy!

22:55.607 --> 22:57.875
 -This sucks.
 -KARI: You can do it.

22:57.876 --> 22:59.477
 GRANT:
 I've got climbing experience.

22:59.478 --> 23:02.478
 But there's nothing to hold on
 to up there except for the rope.

23:02.881 --> 23:05.182
 TORY: Pretend like
 your life depends on it.

23:05.183 --> 23:06.450
 'Cause it kind of does.

23:06.451 --> 23:09.451
 GRANT: So I just thank God
 I got those big knots in there,

23:09.488 --> 23:12.089
 'cause if I didn't have that,
 I'd be done.

23:12.090 --> 23:14.291
 KARI: Oh, Grant.
 You're doing so good.

23:14.292 --> 23:16.660
 TORY: You're almost there, dude.
 You're halfway there!

23:16.661 --> 23:18.496
 KARI: The sheets
 are totally holding you up.

23:18.497 --> 23:19.697
 GRANT:
 There were a couple places

23:19.698 --> 23:21.532
 where I couldn't quite get
 a foothold,

23:21.533 --> 23:23.567
 and the rope just slipped
 through my hands,

23:23.568 --> 23:25.603
 and that's where I got
 these hideous rope burns,

23:25.604 --> 23:28.038
 which are really,
 really hurting.

23:28.039 --> 23:29.673
 TORY:
 Look at the pain in his face.

23:29.674 --> 23:31.609
 Freedom's like 20 feet away.

23:31.610 --> 23:32.777
 KARI: Yeah!

23:32.778 --> 23:34.245
 GRANT:
 Ow. Ow!

23:34.246 --> 23:35.379
 KARI:
 Oh, yes!

23:35.380 --> 23:37.715
 Yes, yes, yes!

23:37.716 --> 23:38.783
 Yeah!

23:38.784 --> 23:41.285
 TORY: Let go!
 You're there, dude!

23:41.286 --> 23:43.053
 -Yeah!
 -Yeah!

23:43.054 --> 23:44.588
 -You're free!
 -GRANT: I'm free!

23:44.589 --> 23:46.390
 -I'm free!
 -KARI: Confirmed!

23:46.391 --> 23:47.958
 Ow!

23:47.959 --> 23:49.026
 NARRATOR: Freedom!

23:49.027 --> 23:51.595
 But with a bad case
 of rope burns.

23:51.596 --> 23:53.130
 You did it!

23:53.131 --> 23:54.965
 The good news is,
 I can totally see

23:54.966 --> 23:56.367
 why they put this in movies.

23:56.368 --> 23:59.368
 Because the entire time,
 the bedsheet was solid.

23:59.638 --> 24:02.573
 There was no ripping,
 no tearing,

24:02.574 --> 24:04.475
 no giving way of the bedsheet.

24:04.476 --> 24:05.476
 That was solid.

24:05.477 --> 24:06.977
 And, you know, if I had been

24:06.978 --> 24:09.647
 in a little bit better
 physical condition,

24:09.648 --> 24:12.648
 I probably would have gotten
 down that no problem.

24:12.651 --> 24:15.651
 NARRATOR: And what that means is
 that scaling the jailhouse wall

24:16.121 --> 24:18.689
 with a bedsheet rope
 is confirmed.

24:18.690 --> 24:21.690
 I'm free!

24:23.795 --> 24:24.929
 For those playing along at home,

24:24.930 --> 24:26.730
 here's where we stand so far
 in the myth

24:26.731 --> 24:29.333
 that jamming a flagpole into
 the front spokes of a motorcycle

24:29.334 --> 24:32.334
 will cause it
 to flip up in the air.

24:32.904 --> 24:35.272
 We've gotten the motorcycle
 wheel up to 50 miles an hour

24:35.273 --> 24:38.273
 and found out that yes,
 a human is totally capable

24:38.543 --> 24:41.543
 of jamming a flagpole into that
 front wheel and stopping it.

24:43.648 --> 24:45.015
 We broke some stuff.

24:45.016 --> 24:46.283
 The question now is,

24:46.284 --> 24:49.053
 if you're doing that
 to a motorcycle that's moving,

24:49.054 --> 24:51.455
 will it have the effect
 that the myth states?

24:51.456 --> 24:54.456
 The bike immediately stops
 and starts to cartwheel

24:54.759 --> 24:56.360
 while going up in the air.

24:56.361 --> 24:57.862
 Now we're gonna see
 what happens for real.

24:57.863 --> 25:00.464
 NARRATOR:
 And with the crowd expectant,

25:00.465 --> 25:03.465
 the teams set up and step up
 for the first test

25:03.802 --> 25:05.536
 at 25 miles per hour.

25:05.537 --> 25:06.804
 -You know what I hope?
 -What?

25:06.805 --> 25:08.739
 -I hope it works.
 -Me too.

25:08.740 --> 25:10.040
 All right.
 Let's start it.

25:10.041 --> 25:13.041
 NARRATOR: Buster, looking
 every inch a crash-test biker,

25:14.045 --> 25:17.045
 tailgates the truck,
 ready for his moment of glory.

25:18.350 --> 25:19.984
 WILL:
 20 miles per hour.

25:19.985 --> 25:22.553
 NARRATOR: And once the team
 are at test speed...

25:22.554 --> 25:24.221
 -25.
 -NARRATOR:... Adam calls it.

25:24.222 --> 25:27.222
 Firing in 3, 2, 1.

25:28.660 --> 25:31.061
 JAMIE: Ah, it went through.
 It stopped the wheel.

25:31.062 --> 25:32.229
 Okay, Will, stop.

25:32.230 --> 25:35.230
 ADAM:
 Slow down and stop.

25:36.501 --> 25:38.669
 NARRATOR:
 It all happened pretty fast.

25:38.670 --> 25:40.304
 But a quick look
 at the high speed

25:40.305 --> 25:43.305
 confirms the Rube Goldberg-esque
 rig worked like a dream.

25:44.943 --> 25:47.545
 Jamie hit the switch.
 Buster was released.

25:47.546 --> 25:49.680
 ADAM: Oh, I see it
 clicking the switch.

25:49.681 --> 25:51.248
 NARRATOR:
 The cannon fired,

25:51.249 --> 25:54.151
 and the flagpole was jammed
 into the spokes...

25:54.152 --> 25:57.152
 ADAM: Dude!
 The timing was just dead-on.

25:57.289 --> 25:59.557
 NARRATOR:... giving Buster
 a taste of asphalt.

25:59.558 --> 26:01.625
 How you doing, buddy?

26:01.626 --> 26:04.595
 NARRATOR: But there was no sign
 of the mythical flip.

26:04.596 --> 26:06.163
 ADAM:
 It couldn't be better.

26:06.164 --> 26:08.032
 But I didn't see
 no bike-o flip-o.

26:08.033 --> 26:10.601
 NARRATOR:
 Yep, no bike-o flip-o.

26:10.602 --> 26:13.070
 More of a bike-o topple-o.

26:13.071 --> 26:14.838
 So, what's next?

26:14.839 --> 26:16.273
 JAMIE:
 The next thing we're gonna do

26:16.274 --> 26:17.808
 is ramp the speed up
 a little bit

26:17.809 --> 26:20.809
 so that the bike will tend to
 want to stay upright for longer,

26:21.313 --> 26:23.914
 and we'll probably get a little
 more energy in the process,

26:23.915 --> 26:26.750
 which means a bigger flip
 if we're gonna get one at all.

26:26.751 --> 26:28.819
 NARRATOR:
 So it's take two.

26:28.820 --> 26:29.987
 ADAM:
 Holding up well.

26:29.988 --> 26:32.022
 NARRATOR: And this time,
 they take the truck to 40.

26:32.023 --> 26:33.457
 WILL:
 40 miles per hour.

26:33.458 --> 26:36.458
 Okay, firing in 3, 2, 1, go.

26:37.462 --> 26:39.630
 Oh!

26:39.631 --> 26:41.865
 -[ Laughs ]
 -JAMIE: Okay, he can stop.

26:41.866 --> 26:44.535
 -Tell him to stop.
 -[ Laughing ] Stop.

26:44.536 --> 26:46.570
 NARRATOR:
 So, the additional momentum

26:46.571 --> 26:49.571
 didn't help
 the bike get airborne.

26:49.941 --> 26:52.676
 Instead,
 that extra energy was used

26:52.677 --> 26:55.677
 to snap the flagpole in half.

26:56.881 --> 26:59.881
 You know what?
 That right there is the test.

27:00.418 --> 27:02.920
 -You know, that's the test.
 -Yeah.

27:02.921 --> 27:05.589
 And it didn't work.
 It broke the stick.

27:05.590 --> 27:08.025
 ADAM: I think that was the
 circumstances of the myth there.

27:08.026 --> 27:10.060
 We got the bike going
 at 40 miles per hour.

27:10.061 --> 27:12.229
 We got the stick firing
 perfectly into the spokes.

27:12.230 --> 27:14.965
 It didn't stop the bike.
 It didn't flip the bike.

27:14.966 --> 27:17.534
 And it broke the stick.

27:17.535 --> 27:18.669
 JAMIE:
 So, what's next?

27:18.670 --> 27:20.738
 Stronger stick.
 That was the circumstances.

27:20.739 --> 27:23.739
 Let's try and get the results
 with a big, fat, steel stick.

27:24.175 --> 27:25.576
 -Steel it is.
 -Mm-hmm.

27:25.577 --> 27:28.577
 NARRATOR: Yep, just like Buster,
 the myth is down,

27:28.747 --> 27:31.747
 but not quite out.

27:32.751 --> 27:35.119
 Kari, Tory, and Grant
 have had success

27:35.120 --> 27:38.120
 with the first of
 their rappel-to-freedom tests.

27:38.390 --> 27:40.124
 KARI: Yeah!

27:40.125 --> 27:41.592
 -You're free!
 -GRANT: I'm free!

27:41.593 --> 27:42.893
 I'm free!

27:42.894 --> 27:45.396
 This myth
 is absolutely confirmed,

27:45.397 --> 27:47.431
 and I love it
 when myths are confirmed.

27:47.432 --> 27:48.832
 The rope did not break.

27:48.833 --> 27:51.833
 You can make a bedsheet rope
 and escape from jail.

27:52.003 --> 27:53.537
 Let's not air this
 in the prisons.

27:53.538 --> 27:55.506
 NARRATOR:
 That's one down -- literally.

27:55.507 --> 27:57.074
 I'm free!

27:57.075 --> 27:58.275
 NARRATOR:
 With two to go.

27:58.276 --> 27:59.410
 KARI:
 I'm not afraid of heights,

27:59.411 --> 28:01.178
 but I am really afraid
 of falling,

28:01.179 --> 28:03.147
 and I'm not a mountain climber.

28:03.148 --> 28:05.315
 This will be the first time
 I really will have done

28:05.316 --> 28:08.316
 anything remotely like this,
 so yeah, I'm nervous.

28:09.454 --> 28:12.454
 Oh, my God.
 I want to throw up.

28:12.557 --> 28:13.557
 [ Laughs ]

28:13.558 --> 28:15.192
 NARRATOR:
 And no wonder she's nervous.

28:15.193 --> 28:18.193
 It's clear hair isn't exactly
 an ideal rope-making material.

28:20.298 --> 28:22.599
 GRANT: I was watching her
 form the rope,

28:22.600 --> 28:25.102
 and there were many times
 where she had to take it apart

28:25.103 --> 28:27.905
 because she would test it
 and it would just go "fwshh!"

28:27.906 --> 28:29.640
 She's got multiple strands,
 you know,

28:29.641 --> 28:32.641
 forming a big, thick rope
 of hair, but I don't know.

28:33.912 --> 28:36.780
 At this point, my confidence
 isn't especially high.

28:36.781 --> 28:38.382
 NARRATOR:
 And neither is Kari's.

28:38.383 --> 28:41.383
 Whose hair-ball idea is this?

28:41.519 --> 28:44.354
 NARRATOR: Well, it's
 a "hair"-brain plan, for sure,

28:44.355 --> 28:46.557
 but it's too late
 to turn back now.

28:46.558 --> 28:49.558
 We're about to find out if
 that hairy lifeline will cut it.

28:52.030 --> 28:55.030
 TORY: Man. Oh.

28:55.033 --> 28:57.701
 GRANT: It's looking pretty good
 so far, actually.

28:57.702 --> 28:59.536
 TORY: Well, the hair is --
 It's holding up.

28:59.537 --> 29:00.637
 GRANT:
 That's great.

29:00.638 --> 29:02.606
 TORY: It's incredible
 how strong it is.

29:02.607 --> 29:04.875
 -Whoa!
 -GRANT: Whoa!

29:04.876 --> 29:07.745
 NARRATOR: It defies belief,
 but Kari's descent

29:07.746 --> 29:09.713
 is being supported
 by nothing more

29:09.714 --> 29:12.714
 than a 1 40-feet-long
 triple-braided ponytail.

29:13.918 --> 29:15.285
 How's it going, Kari?

29:15.286 --> 29:16.520
 KARI:
 I see split ends.

29:16.521 --> 29:18.122
 TORY: You should have used
 conditioner.

29:18.123 --> 29:19.723
 KARI:
 There's split ends!

29:19.724 --> 29:21.325
 NARRATOR:
 Hair-care issues aside,

29:21.326 --> 29:24.326
 Kari's descent is going
 spectacularly well.

29:24.796 --> 29:25.996
 TORY:
 You're almost free!

29:25.997 --> 29:27.831
 NARRATOR:
 And her technique of sliding

29:27.832 --> 29:30.701
 instead of climbing
 is just perfect.

29:30.702 --> 29:33.070
 -Yeah!
 -You're free!

29:33.071 --> 29:34.271
 GRANT:
 You did it!

29:34.272 --> 29:36.073
 The hair didn't break.

29:36.074 --> 29:38.876
 I've got to say,
 I'm totally amazed.

29:38.877 --> 29:40.344
 My hands -- little jacked.

29:40.345 --> 29:43.345
 This rope is composed
 of hair that's braided.

29:44.749 --> 29:46.183
 And if you look at it,

29:46.184 --> 29:49.184
 it's actually kind of springy,
 which is just crazy.

29:50.121 --> 29:51.121
 It's effective.

29:51.122 --> 29:53.123
 Disgusting, but effective.

29:53.124 --> 29:54.291
 Yeah!

29:54.292 --> 29:56.160
 Oh, my God!
 That was so scary!

29:56.161 --> 29:57.861
 -Yeah?
 -And the hair didn't break.

29:57.862 --> 29:59.763
 I can't believe it didn't break.

29:59.764 --> 30:02.699
 KARI: It was like I'd slide,
 grab a knot, slide, grab a knot.

30:02.700 --> 30:04.635
 But the whole time, I was just
 like, "It's coming undone,

30:04.636 --> 30:06.937
 it's coming undone, it's coming
 undone, it's coming undone!"

30:06.938 --> 30:09.273
 When I was right close to
 the ground, I had about a foot.

30:09.274 --> 30:10.908
 Then I kind of dropped
 a little bit.

30:10.909 --> 30:12.843
 That's the only time
 I actually felt the rope

30:12.844 --> 30:15.112
 kind of -- the belay --
 was the last foot.

30:15.113 --> 30:18.113
 The whole time, that was
 sheer human hair strength.

30:19.918 --> 30:21.752
 NARRATOR:
 Incredible, but true.

30:21.753 --> 30:23.287
 But unlike the bedsheets,

30:23.288 --> 30:26.288
 the guys are reluctant
 to call this one confirmed.

30:26.791 --> 30:28.725
 TORY: The hair worked,
 and it didn't break.

30:28.726 --> 30:30.594
 I mean, it's not
 the most practical technique,

30:30.595 --> 30:32.262
 but if you can get
 that amount of hair

30:32.263 --> 30:35.263
 and braid it together,
 you can make rope and escape.

30:36.000 --> 30:38.035
 NARRATOR: Yeah,
 unless your name's Rapunzel,

30:38.036 --> 30:40.604
 getting that amount of hair
 could be an issue.

30:40.605 --> 30:43.605
 But as a mythical rope-making
 material, it does actually work.

30:47.779 --> 30:48.378
 ADAM: 3...

30:48.379 --> 30:49.980
 NARRATOR:
 On the motorcycle movie myth,

30:49.981 --> 30:52.981
 Adam and Jamie are having
 a flipping good time.

30:53.351 --> 30:54.885
 I didn't see no bike-o flip-o.

30:54.886 --> 30:56.687
 NARRATOR:
 But so far there's been no sign

30:56.688 --> 30:59.688
 of the mythical
 head-over-handlebars flip.

30:59.824 --> 31:01.258
 JAMIE:
 Okay, you can stop.

31:01.259 --> 31:04.259
 NARRATOR: So they decided
 to beef things up a bit.

31:04.495 --> 31:07.495
 So, at 40 miles an hour,
 hickory didn't really cut it.

31:08.166 --> 31:11.166
 So this time,
 we're gonna use a steel pipe.

31:11.302 --> 31:14.302
 This is about eight times
 as heavy, and...

31:15.773 --> 31:17.708
...it's gonna do something
 pretty violent.

31:17.709 --> 31:19.576
 ADAM: Hopefully,
 this is the "it" shot.

31:19.577 --> 31:22.145
 This is either going to flip
 this motorcycle

31:22.146 --> 31:24.281
 or prove once and for all
 that it's totally not possible.

31:24.282 --> 31:26.984
 -I hope this works.
 -What's not to work?

31:26.985 --> 31:29.853
 [ Both laugh ]

31:29.854 --> 31:31.889
 Oh, so many things.

31:31.890 --> 31:33.957
 NARRATOR: But if it goes
 according to plan,

31:33.958 --> 31:36.958
 Buster will soon be taking
 a short, dizzying flight

31:37.562 --> 31:40.562
 with a mandatory crash landing.

31:40.932 --> 31:43.433
 Okay. Pull in 3, 2, 1.

31:43.434 --> 31:45.535
 Go!

31:45.536 --> 31:48.536
 Oh!
 [ Laughs ]

31:50.008 --> 31:53.008
 Give me five there!

31:55.513 --> 31:58.513
 NARRATOR: Another
 smooth execution by the rig,

31:58.650 --> 32:01.518
 and you could say
 the guys are pleased.

32:01.519 --> 32:03.620
 Well, that seemed to work
 just beautifully.

32:03.621 --> 32:04.988
 It doesn't get
 any prettier than that.

32:04.989 --> 32:07.257
 -JAMIE: No. It was flawless.
 -And the bike did not flip.

32:07.258 --> 32:08.825
 JAMIE: No.
 The tires skidded.

32:08.826 --> 32:10.761
 You know, that's it.
 That's the perfect test.

32:10.762 --> 32:12.129
 ADAM:
 It's forward momentum.

32:12.130 --> 32:14.698
 It doesn't transfer immediately
 to vertical momentum.

32:14.699 --> 32:15.966
 It makes all the sense
 in the world

32:15.967 --> 32:17.267
 now that I've seen it happen.

32:17.268 --> 32:19.503
 JAMIE: You know, you could stop
 the bad guy that way

32:19.504 --> 32:21.138
 if you happen to have
 a steel pipe,

32:21.139 --> 32:22.839
 but it's not getting airborne.

32:22.840 --> 32:25.840
 It won't happen.
 It's gonna do exactly that.

32:25.843 --> 32:27.711
 ADAM:
 Dude, that totally worked.

32:27.712 --> 32:29.012
 Freakin' "A."

32:29.013 --> 32:31.281
 The most important thing
 to keep in mind about this test

32:31.282 --> 32:34.282
 is the traction between
 this wheel and the road surface.

32:34.652 --> 32:35.986
 Nice work, Buster!

32:35.987 --> 32:38.455
 If you bring the wheel
 to a dead stop

32:38.456 --> 32:41.224
 like you will if you put
 a stick between the spokes,

32:41.225 --> 32:42.359
 it's gonna skid.

32:42.360 --> 32:44.061
 You're gonna lose control.

32:44.062 --> 32:46.596
 It'll slip out from under
 the bike, and it's all over.

32:46.597 --> 32:49.597
 It will not get it airborne
 like it did in the movie.

32:50.268 --> 32:52.502
 Oh! So satisfying.

32:52.503 --> 32:55.503
 NARRATOR: So, no bike-o flip-o
 even with the mayo.

32:56.474 --> 32:57.975
 ADAM:
 You know what we have to do now.

32:57.976 --> 33:00.976
 We have to finish on a bike
 that's... doing a flip.

33:02.013 --> 33:04.281
 Hook or by crook,
 we have to finish with that.

33:04.282 --> 33:07.282
 Physics, one, movies, zero.

33:07.552 --> 33:09.419
 NARRATOR:
 And so it's back to the shop

33:09.420 --> 33:12.420
 to square the account and find
 out the physics of film effects.

33:13.458 --> 33:14.524
 [ Horn beeping ]

33:14.525 --> 33:15.826
 Dude, check this out.

33:15.827 --> 33:18.495
 It looks like this whole scene
 is just a trick of editing.

33:18.496 --> 33:20.097
 You can see
 that when the bike takes off,

33:20.098 --> 33:23.098
 it's totally stationary, and if
 I frame forward a couple frames,

33:24.202 --> 33:26.036
 you can see a small explosion
 underneath.

33:26.037 --> 33:28.372
 That's a classic Hollywood
 sleight of hand.

33:28.373 --> 33:30.741
 Yeah, it's pretty clear if we're
 gonna do this Hollywood-style,

33:30.742 --> 33:33.210
 we're gonna need some explosives
 to get that bike in the air.

33:33.211 --> 33:35.579
 -We need a boom.
 -Exactly.

33:35.580 --> 33:38.148
 NARRATOR:
 Yep, so the key is TNT.

33:38.149 --> 33:39.616
 And with that in mind,

33:39.617 --> 33:42.617
 our special-effects specialists
 get back to work.

33:42.687 --> 33:44.688
 JAMIE: This is what is known
 as a mortar.

33:44.689 --> 33:47.024
 Now, this is what is going to
 make the bike

33:47.025 --> 33:50.025
 do what we couldn't do
 with a stick through the spokes.

33:50.428 --> 33:51.962
 We're gonna fill this
 with gunpowder.

33:51.963 --> 33:53.964
 We're gonna put it
 underneath the bike,

33:53.965 --> 33:56.965
 and it's gonna fire
 a bunch of black powder,

33:57.402 --> 33:59.136
 shooting the bike
 way up in the air

33:59.137 --> 34:00.871
 and spinning while it does it.

34:00.872 --> 34:03.807
 NARRATOR: To survive that
 black-powder-powered flight,

34:03.808 --> 34:05.742
 the bike gets a once-over
 from Adam.

34:05.743 --> 34:08.245
 ADAM: I reinforced
 its skeletal structure

34:08.246 --> 34:10.480
 so that it can be punched
 from behind the engine

34:10.481 --> 34:13.016
 and fly up in the air to glory.

34:13.016 --> 34:16.016
 NARRATOR: Sounds great, unless
 your name happens to be Buster.

34:18.121 --> 34:21.121
 To get to the, uh, bottom
 of the toilet-paper jailbreak...

34:22.659 --> 34:25.195
 Oh, this prison food's
 killing me!

34:25.196 --> 34:26.196
 [ Farts ]

34:26.197 --> 34:29.197
 You need to put more fiber
 in the damn food!

34:29.833 --> 34:32.268
 NARRATOR:... Tory has taken
 a swipe at making a rope

34:32.270 --> 34:35.270
 from genuine one-ply
 perforated prison poop paper.

34:36.440 --> 34:38.108
 So my toilet-paper rope is done.

34:38.109 --> 34:40.543
 It's taken me a long time,
 and it looks like rope.

34:40.545 --> 34:42.813
 However, it's still
 only toilet paper.

34:42.813 --> 34:45.549
 I'm hoping it's gonna be strong
 enough to hold up my weight.

34:45.550 --> 34:48.351
 KARI: [ High-pitched voice ]
 His chances are made of paper.

34:48.351 --> 34:51.351
 GRANT: His escape technique's
 paper-thin!

34:52.023 --> 34:53.456
 [ Normal voice ]
 We better get out of here,

34:53.458 --> 34:55.425
 or they're gonna put us
 in the loony bin.

34:55.426 --> 34:57.828
 Toilet-paper rope escape

34:57.829 --> 35:00.797
 is probably
 the stupidest idea ever.

35:00.798 --> 35:03.798
 It's not that stupid.
 You've had stupider ideas.

35:03.968 --> 35:06.703
 I'm gonna kick your butt
 if I survive, Grant.

35:06.704 --> 35:09.704
 Watch that first step.
 She's a doozy.

35:09.774 --> 35:12.476
 NARRATOR: And that first step
 is also the crucial moment

35:12.477 --> 35:15.477
 when nothing but toilet paper
 is taking Tory's weight.

35:16.447 --> 35:19.447
 KARI: [ Laughing ]
 Oh, my God!

35:19.984 --> 35:20.851
 [Bleep]

35:20.852 --> 35:23.852
 NARRATOR: But, incredibly,
 a few expletives aside,

35:24.155 --> 35:27.155
 it's all going according
 to plan -- sort of.

35:27.725 --> 35:30.560
 TORY: Toilet paper is used
 to wipe your butt,

35:30.561 --> 35:33.330
 not climb down a building.

35:33.331 --> 35:35.732
 NARRATOR: It seems
 the real issue with the tissue

35:35.733 --> 35:37.634
 is finding a firm grip.

35:37.635 --> 35:39.503
 -Oh! Oh!
 -TORY: [ Grunts ]

35:39.504 --> 35:40.971
 I'm off -- [ Grunts ]

35:40.972 --> 35:42.139
 [Bleep]

35:42.140 --> 35:44.241
 [ Groans ]
 [Bleep]

35:44.242 --> 35:46.243
 -Are you okay?
 -[ Weakly ] Yeah.

35:46.244 --> 35:49.244
 NARRATOR: And that right there
 is why we hired the SWAT team.

35:49.814 --> 35:51.314
 Tory slipped.

35:51.315 --> 35:52.949
 -KARI Oh!
 -TORY: [ Grunts ] [Bleep]

35:52.950 --> 35:55.919
 NARRATOR: And if it wasn't
 for the safety harness,

35:55.920 --> 35:57.921
 he was a goner.

35:57.922 --> 36:00.922
 But aside from that sudden
 and terrifying drop...

36:00.992 --> 36:03.293
 GRANT: Yeah, dude,
 you're almost there!

36:03.294 --> 36:06.294
 NARRATOR:... Tory and
 the toilet paper hold firm

36:06.297 --> 36:08.698
 and make it safely
 to terra firma.

36:08.699 --> 36:10.567
 -GRANT: [ Laughs ]
 -Freedom!

36:10.568 --> 36:12.736
 GRANT: Yeah!

36:12.737 --> 36:14.304
 You did it!

36:14.305 --> 36:16.673
 -How's those hands?
 -They're numb!

36:16.674 --> 36:19.674
 Who would've thought toilet
 paper works to escape prison?!

36:21.979 --> 36:22.913
 I'm amazed.

36:22.914 --> 36:25.749
 I'm amazed that the toilet paper
 did not break.

36:25.750 --> 36:28.451
 Freedom!

36:28.452 --> 36:30.787
 At least while he was
 making his way down.

36:30.788 --> 36:33.523
 I'm free.
 I can't walk, but I'm free.

36:33.524 --> 36:36.524
 NARRATOR: Yeah, it broke, but
 it didn't break during the test.

36:36.861 --> 36:39.861
 And so Tory gives toilet paper
 his seal of approval.

36:39.997 --> 36:41.131
 TORY:
 Oh [bleep]

36:41.132 --> 36:44.132
 I'm totally convinced
 that toilet paper used as a rope

36:44.368 --> 36:46.603
 is a plausible way
 to escape from prison.

36:46.604 --> 36:48.471
 You saw it.
 It didn't break.

36:48.472 --> 36:50.674
 It stretched a lot,
 but it didn't break.

36:50.675 --> 36:53.410
 It was incredible.
 Toilet paper.

36:53.411 --> 36:54.878
 It worked!
 We're free!

36:54.879 --> 36:57.847
 That was amazing!
 Two plausibles and a confirmed!

36:57.848 --> 36:59.816
 Hair, toilet paper,
 and bedsheets!

36:59.817 --> 37:02.817
 All right. I'll see you guys
 in Mexico in a month.

37:10.228 --> 37:12.362
 Welcome back.
 Here's where we stand.

37:12.363 --> 37:13.763
 We have already busted the myth

37:13.764 --> 37:16.499
 that if you jam a flagpole
 into the spokes of a motorcycle

37:16.500 --> 37:18.635
 at speed,
 that it will flip end over end.

37:18.636 --> 37:21.636
 Totally not possible
 within the laws of physics.

37:23.708 --> 37:26.243
 Now Jamie and I are gonna do it
 Hollywood-style

37:26.244 --> 37:29.244
 with our favorite tool --
 explosives.

37:29.880 --> 37:32.349
 In Hollywood, also,
 geeky television-show hosts

37:32.350 --> 37:34.918
 get to dress up like
 their favorite movie heroes...

37:34.919 --> 37:36.753
 -[ Whip cracks ]
 -That's the only crack I know.

37:36.754 --> 37:39.422
 I can't... crack like that.
 Ow.

37:39.423 --> 37:42.025
...pretend to be in one
 of their favorite movies.

37:42.026 --> 37:43.627
 [ Whip cracking ]

37:43.628 --> 37:45.295
 All right.
 Let's get to filming.

37:45.296 --> 37:47.897
 NARRATOR: And to make sure
 this silver scene re-creation

37:47.898 --> 37:50.898
 is spot-on, the bike and Buster
 get a makeover

37:51.902 --> 37:54.304
 by the wardrobe department.

37:54.305 --> 37:55.972
 ADAM:
 It looks good.

37:55.973 --> 37:57.574
 NARRATOR:
 And Buster is given no choice

37:57.575 --> 38:00.575
 about his participation
 in the upcoming stunt.

38:00.678 --> 38:03.079
 That's how the old Hollywood
 stunt men used to do it.

38:03.080 --> 38:06.080
 "Wire me in!" they'd scream.
 [ Chuckles ]

38:06.784 --> 38:08.785
 Buster's old-school.

38:08.786 --> 38:11.688
 NARRATOR: With our very own
 member of the Third Reich

38:11.689 --> 38:14.689
 on his bike, the guys,
 with the help of Matt the pyro,

38:15.693 --> 38:18.693
 prepare the mortar that
 will send Buster into the air.

38:19.497 --> 38:21.264
 JAMIE: We've got this mortar
 with the plate

38:21.265 --> 38:22.299
 right on top of it.

38:22.300 --> 38:24.734
 That plate is welded
 to the bottom of the motorcycle.

38:24.735 --> 38:26.303
 It's very secure.

38:26.304 --> 38:28.505
 When that gunpowder goes off,

38:28.506 --> 38:31.141
 the plate is gonna go up,
 and that's all there is to it.

38:31.142 --> 38:33.710
 NARRATOR: With Jamie applying
 the finishing touches,

38:33.711 --> 38:36.711
 Adam takes delivery of
 the final piece of the puzzle.

38:37.381 --> 38:39.482
 Dude, I totally want
 one of these.

38:39.483 --> 38:42.483
 NARRATOR: So now Adam's got
 the ride to go with the outfit.

38:42.853 --> 38:45.853
 Awesome. Look. It's got a seat
 for Jamie and everything.

38:50.161 --> 38:52.729
 Ba-da-da-da!
 Ba-da-da! 

38:52.730 --> 38:55.730
 NARRATOR: And with that out
 of his system, it's stunt time.

38:56.067 --> 38:58.468
 ADAM:
 It's like nerd fantasy camp.

38:58.469 --> 39:00.370
 Okay, so, here's
 how the Mythbusters'

39:00.371 --> 39:02.205
 big-budget movie shot
 is gonna break down.

39:02.206 --> 39:04.107
 Jamie and I will start
 the motorcycle and sidecar

39:04.108 --> 39:06.643
 about 100 feet
 behind our stunt cycle.

39:06.644 --> 39:08.078
 We're gonna drive right past it.

39:08.079 --> 39:09.946
 When we get 100 feet
 ahead of it,

39:09.947 --> 39:12.115
 the pyro's gonna detonate
 the charge in this.

39:12.116 --> 39:15.116
 Our stunt Buster is gonna fly
 up in the air end over end,

39:15.319 --> 39:16.920
 and the long lens
 that we're shooting it from

39:16.921 --> 39:19.921
 is gonna make it look like we're
 a lot closer to the explosion

39:19.924 --> 39:21.324
 than we actually are.

39:21.325 --> 39:22.959
 [ Horn beeping ]

39:22.960 --> 39:25.960
 You ready, old man?
 You got a taste for adventure?

39:26.497 --> 39:28.932
 [ Chuckling ] Okay.
 Here we go.

39:28.933 --> 39:31.933
 [ Engine revving ]

39:32.370 --> 39:35.370
 NARRATOR: So everyone,
 including Buster, is all set.

39:36.107 --> 39:38.141
 Adam and Jamie roll up to speed,

39:38.142 --> 39:41.142
 and Matt waits with his finger
 on the detonator.

39:41.379 --> 39:44.180
 To get the shot,
 the timing, camera angle,

39:44.181 --> 39:47.181
 and flight of the bike
 has to be just so.

39:50.421 --> 39:53.421
 And that couldn't have gone
 better.

39:53.457 --> 39:55.992
 [ Laughs ]
 Well, the timing was perfect.

39:55.993 --> 39:57.460
 If you say so, Junior.

39:57.461 --> 40:00.461
 [ Laughs ]

40:00.464 --> 40:02.832
 NARRATOR:
 Well, let's check the footage.

40:02.833 --> 40:05.833
 The mortar exploded as Adam
 and Jamie hit their mark,

40:06.036 --> 40:09.036
 and Buster, the chasing Nazi
 with a stick in the spokes,

40:09.974 --> 40:12.974
 goes head over handlebars.

40:13.677 --> 40:15.378
 ADAM: [ Laughs ]

40:15.379 --> 40:16.980
 Oh, that's awesome.

40:16.981 --> 40:19.282
 JAMIE: I'm seeing it go
 ass over teakettle.

40:19.283 --> 40:21.351
 ADAM: That's exactly
 what it looks like in the movie.

40:21.352 --> 40:24.320
 NARRATOR: Yep, as
 a quick comparison confirms,

40:24.321 --> 40:26.089
 the guys got the shot.

40:26.090 --> 40:28.124
 ADAM:
 It's beautiful.

40:28.125 --> 40:29.826
 You may watch this
 and still think,

40:29.827 --> 40:31.928
 "I think it could happen
 to the motorcycle

40:31.929 --> 40:33.029
 under the right conditions."

40:33.030 --> 40:36.030
 Let me point out
 this stick in the wheel

40:36.734 --> 40:38.435
 made the motorcycle skid.

40:38.436 --> 40:40.036
 How much energy did it take

40:40.037 --> 40:42.839
 to make the bike go
 completely vertical?

40:42.840 --> 40:45.840
 Enough energy to crush this
 3/8-inch-thick steel plate

40:47.511 --> 40:50.511
 and crack the frame
 in like 19 different places.

40:50.514 --> 40:52.515
 That's a hell of a lot
 more energy

40:52.516 --> 40:54.951
 than you can generate
 with a wooden stick.

40:54.952 --> 40:57.952
 Myth busted.

41:00.191 --> 41:02.892
 And now, Buster, for doing such
 a good job, gets his reward.

41:02.893 --> 41:04.127
 He really likes it this way.

41:04.128 --> 41:07.128
 Nice work, Buster!
 Nice work!

